irie farmers. Through interviews with producers, industry organizations, and biochemical companies, Eaton demonstrates how the inclusion of producer interests was integral to the coalition's success in voicing concerns about environmental implications, international market opposition to GMOs, and the lack of transparency and democracy in Canadian biotech policy and regulation. Growing Resistance is a fascinating study of successful coalition building, of the need to balance local and global concerns in activist movements, and of the powerful forces vying for control of food production.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFarmersxPolitical activityxCanada. 0aFarmersxPolitical activityzCanada. 0aTransgenic plantsxPolitical aspectsxCanada. 0aTransgenic plantsxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aWheat tradexPrairie Provinces. 0aWheat tradezPrairie Provinces. 0aWheatxGenetic engineeringxCanada. 0aWheatxGenetic engineeringzCanada. 0aWheatxPrairie Provinces. 0aWheatzPrairie Provinces. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh  aGMO.  aMonsanto.  aagriculture.  abiotechnology.  afarming.  afood security.  agenetically modified.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755435340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554353/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles